[3] USAID: contest seeks novel tools for the fight against Ebola
Date: 12 Dec 2014
Source: NY Times [edited]
http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/13/health/ebola-contest-brings-ideas-for-cooling-suits-and-virus-repellents.html?_r=0


[See Photo in Source: A prototype for one of the protective suits in contention for the USAID "Grand Challenges" award. Credit: John Hopkins University/Jhpiego]

The well-prepared Ebola fighter in West Africa may soon have some new options: protective gear that zips off like a wet suit, ice-cold underwear to make life inside the sweltering suits more bearable, or lotions that go on like bug spray and kill or repel the lethal virus.

Those ideas are among the contenders to win the Ebola "Grand Challenges" contest announced in October [2014] by the United States Agency for International Development, or among those being considered by the agency without having formally entered the contest... Wendy Taylor, director of USAID's Center for Accelerating Innovation and Impact... said the agency would spend about USD 1.7 million testing the most promising possibilities.

A higher-tech alternative is Qore athletic gear, which includes compression sleeves and shorts that press cooling packs to the forearm and groin, where arteries run close to the surface. Testing is needed, Ms. Taylor said, to see whether the vest is comfortable enough and the sleeves cooling enough. Doctors and nurses working in midday tropical heat are often near collapse after 45 minutes. Prolonging that period would let them see more patients.

Some clothing, including various brands of cooling undergarments, are repurposed off-the-shelf products. The heavy-duty SteeleVest, for example, is used by the military, some industrial workers, and, according to the company's website, vacationers and fishermen. Technologically, it is simple: a fabric vest with pockets into which gel packs fresh out of the freezer are inserted.

[Byline: Donald G. McNeil Jr.]

